      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software must hold a documented QA plan with version control and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under an FDA-validated installation with documented QA procedures, version-controlled input decks, and a regression test suite covering linear static and contact analyses. Achieved level 2 satisfies the required level for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks must demonstrate correct implementation of linear elastic and contact formulations against known analytic solutions.",
      "rationale": "Ansys has been verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems LE1 and LE10 for linear elasticity and Hertzian contact benchmarks. Results agree within 0.5% of analytic solutions, satisfying level 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change less than 5% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted on screw shank and rod contact region. Stiffness QoI changed by 3.8% from coarse to medium and 0.9% from medium to fine mesh. Final mesh (fine, ~480k elements) adopted. Richardson extrapolation applied; GCI < 1.2%. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must fall below 1e-6 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solver (SPARSE) employed; force and displacement residuals monitored across all 20 load steps. Maximum residual 4.3e-8, well below the 1e-6 criterion. Newton-Raphson convergence achieved in ≤6 iterations per load step. Achieved level 2 exceeds required level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup and boundary conditions must be documented.",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed by a second FEA analyst independent of the primary modeler. Boundary conditions, material assignments, contact pair definitions, and load application points verified against the ASTM F1717 test fixture drawings. One minor discrepancy in rod constraint identified and corrected prior to final runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions must be documented and justified relative to the physics of interest; sensitivity to key assumptions must be assessed.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material model justified for sub-yield loading regime; bilinear isotropic hardening adopted for post-yield response. Frictional contact (μ=0.2, titanium-on-titanium) selected based on published tribology data. Sensitivity analysis on friction coefficient (0.1–0.3) showed less than 4% variation in stiffness QoI, supporting the nominal value. Large-displacement formulation (NLGEOM ON) activated for the 40 mm displacement load case."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to measurements on the actual test specimens or certified material data sheets.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V ELI material properties (E=114 GPa, σy=880 MPa) sourced from ASTM F136 certificate of conformance for the specific material lot used in bench testing. Screw and rod geometry digitized from CMM measurements on three representative specimens; nominal CAD used for the remaining specimens with dimensional tolerances applied as sensitivity bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test sample size must be sufficient to characterize experimental variability; samples must be representative of the device design.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6; Lab 2: n=5). All constructs assembled from the same material lot and manufacturing batch. Coefficient of variation for stiffness 6.5%, consistent with literature values for similar constructs. Sample size provides adequate statistical power for the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the clinically relevant range of loading configurations and environmental conditions.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted at a single load angle (5°) per ASTM F1717 protocol. The clinical loading environment includes variable angulation and dynamic cycling not captured in this static single-condition test. Achieved level 2 falls below the required level 3; this known gap is documented as a limitation of the ASTM F1717 protocol scope and is accepted given the regulatory precedent for this test method."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters must be demonstrably equivalent to the experimental conditions used for validation.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry, screw insertion depth, rod diameter (5.5 mm), inter-screw distance (44 mm), and crosshead displacement rate all replicated in the FEA model from the documented test setup. Material property equivalency confirmed via certificate of conformance traceability. Boundary conditions reproduce the pin-and-roller fixture kinematics verified by fixture drawing review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval must be below 1.96 for all QoIs; percentage difference must be below 10%.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both the percentage difference criterion and the E/uval criterion. E/uval values of 0.61, 0.88, and 1.12 are all below 1.96. Percentage differences of 2.0%, 2.1%, and 2.8% are all well within the 10% bound. The validation metric framework follows ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation must be directly relevant to the clinical and regulatory decision being supported.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary mechanical endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the regulatory submission requirements for pedicle screw construct performance. These QoIs are mechanistically related to the failure modes of concern (screw fracture, rod fracture, construct loosening)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must closely match the COU in terms of geometry, loading, and device configuration.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the same device design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw) under the same ASTM F1717 protocol as the COU. Laboratory bench testing directly replicates the conditions the FEA model is intended to predict. The validation-to-COU mapping is one-to-one with no extrapolation required in geometry, loading mode, or material system."
    }
